<h2>What is the secret to making good rice?</h2>
<p>I start with the finger method. It is an ancient Chinese secret. Start by washing your rice. Then, when you fill your rice into the pot, you stick your finger into it, and as the top of your finger is touching the rice, you fill the water up to the first knuckle. That is, for me, the trick to making perfect rice.</p>
<p>I bring my water to a boil with my rice in it. By the time it comes to a boil, the rice and water level is usually about even and then I cover it up, put it on the lowest heat possible on the stove, and cook it for exactly 22 minutes. That makes perfect rice every single time. If you are not using a rice cooker and you are cooking on the stove, practice, because there is a definite feel to making rice.</p>
<h2>What is the ratio of water to rice for perfect rice?</h2>
<p>Again, itâ€™s the finger method. I donâ€™t understand how it works scientifically because it doesnâ€™t matter how much rice you have; the finger method works every single time.</p>
<div class="wp-caption alignnone" id="attachment_140131"><div class="article-content-image"><div class="corus-image-wrapper" style="max-width:1024px;margin:auto"><img alt="Tuna onigiri on a plate" loading="lazy" width="1024" height="682" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" class="wp-image-140131 size-large" style="color:transparent;width:100%;height:auto" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" srcSet="https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/tuna-onigiri-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=640&amp;quality=75 640w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/tuna-onigiri-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=704&amp;quality=75 704w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/tuna-onigiri-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=750&amp;quality=75 750w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/tuna-onigiri-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=828&amp;quality=75 828w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/tuna-onigiri-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=856&amp;quality=75 856w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/tuna-onigiri-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=1080&amp;quality=75 1080w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/tuna-onigiri-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=1200&amp;quality=75 1200w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/tuna-onigiri-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=1920&amp;quality=75 1920w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/tuna-onigiri-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=2048&amp;quality=75 2048w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/tuna-onigiri-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=3840&amp;quality=75 3840w" src="https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/tuna-onigiri-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=3840&amp;quality=75"/></div></div><p class="wp-caption-text" id="caption-attachment-140131">Get the recipe: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://www.foodnetwork.ca/recipe/easy-tuna-onigiri/">Tuna Onigiri</a></p></div>
<h2>Does all rice need to be soaked before cooking?</h2>
<p>Ideally, it should be, but it depends on what you are doing with the rice. For the most part, if you are steaming your rice, you want to rinse itÂ a few timesÂ toÂ clean itÂ andÂ allow it to slightly rehydrate. Parboiled rice, like boxed rice that can cook in minutes, does not need to be rinsed.</p>
<h2>What are your favourite ways to season rice?</h2>
<p>I usually like to add star anise, a half stick of cinnamon and a little pinch of salt.</p>
<h2>Do you recommend seasoning rice before or after cooking?</h2>
<p>I actually like seasoning my water just before cooking so Iâ€™ll add a pinch of salt.</p>
<div class="wp-caption alignnone" id="attachment_135187"><div class="article-content-image"><div class="corus-image-wrapper" style="max-width:1024px;margin:auto"><img alt="Vegetable pulao, ready to serve" loading="lazy" width="1024" height="682" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" class="wp-image-135187 size-large" style="color:transparent;width:100%;height:auto" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" srcSet="https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/vegetable-pulao-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=640&amp;quality=75 640w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/vegetable-pulao-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=704&amp;quality=75 704w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/vegetable-pulao-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=750&amp;quality=75 750w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/vegetable-pulao-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=828&amp;quality=75 828w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/vegetable-pulao-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=856&amp;quality=75 856w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/vegetable-pulao-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=1080&amp;quality=75 1080w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/vegetable-pulao-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=1200&amp;quality=75 1200w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/vegetable-pulao-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=1920&amp;quality=75 1920w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/vegetable-pulao-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=2048&amp;quality=75 2048w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/vegetable-pulao-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=3840&amp;quality=75 3840w" src="https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/vegetable-pulao-feat.jpg?w=1024?w=3840&amp;quality=75"/></div></div><p class="wp-caption-text" id="caption-attachment-135187">Get the recipe: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://www.foodnetwork.ca/recipe/spiced-vegetable-pulao/">Spiced Vegetable Pulao</a></p></div>
<h2>What less common rice varieties should our readers be trying?</h2>
<p>Some of the other less common varieties to try are Riceberry Rice and Thai sticky rice which is also called glutinous or sweet rice. Riceberry rice is a long-grain rice, well-known for its deep purple hue, getting its distinctive colour from naturally occurring flavonoid pigments known to have antioxidant properties.</p>
<h2>Do you recommend cooking rice in a rice cooker or on the stovetop?</h2>
<p>I always cook rice on a stovetop, but if you do have a very good rice cooker, it can be quite amazing. Kate [my wife] definitely swears by the Tiger Rice Cooker, but when I make rice and want it to come out absolutely perfect every single time, I do it on top of the stove using the finger method.</p><div class="ad-wrapper article-ad-paragraph"><span class="ad-label">ADVERTISEMENT</span><div class="ad-slot article-ad-paragraph-wrapper adunitContainer"><div class="adBox" id="article-ad-2"></div></div></div>
<p>Read more: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://www.foodnetwork.ca/article/leftover-rice-recipes/">Leftover Rice Recipes That Make Meal Prep So Much Easier</a></p>


