esoothing congee\u003c/a\u003e, or to soak up all of the sauces of \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/recipe/this-sweet-and-sour-shrimp-and-tofu-recipe-is-better-than-takeout/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003ea tangy stir fry\u003c/a\u003e, it\u0026rsquo;s endlessly versatile and so comforting. But that perfectly starchy carb can be a difficult ingredient to master, so we caught up with \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/article/chef-nick-liu-from-contestant-to-judge/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003eChef Nick Liu\u003c/a\u003e \u0026mdash; Executive Chef \u0026amp; Partner at the critically-acclaimed DaiLo in Toronto, New Asian cuisine expert and \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/tag/wall-of-chefs/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003e\u003cem\u003eWall of Chefs\u003c/em\u003e chef\u003c/a\u003e \u0026mdash; to find out his tips and tricks for making the best rice ever, including his secret fail-safe method. Read on for rice 101.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRelated: \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/article/delectable-rice-recipes/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003e7 Delectable Rice Recipes to Enjoy\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv id=\"attachment_91677\" style=\"width: 898px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-91677\" class=\"wp-image-91677 size-large\" src=\"https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Nick-Liu-resized-main-choice.jpg?w=888\" alt=\"Chef Nick Liu\" width=\"888\" height=\"590\" srcset=\"https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Nick-Liu-resized-main-choice.jpg 888w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Nick-Liu-resized-main-choice.jpg?resize=300,199 300w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Nick-Liu-resized-main-choice.jpg?resize=768,510 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 888px) 100vw, 888px\"\u003e\u003cp id=\"caption-attachment-91677\" class=\"wp-caption-text\"\u003eChef Nick Liu\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eWhat is the secret to making good rice?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI start with the finger method. It is an ancient Chinese secret. Start by washing your rice. Then, when you fill your rice into the pot, you stick your finger into it, and as the top of your finger is touching the rice, you fill the water up to the first knuckle. That is, for me, the trick to making perfect rice.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI bring my water to a boil with my rice in it. By the time it comes to a boil, the rice and water level is usually about even and then I cover it up, put it on the lowest heat possible on the stove, and cook it for exactly 22 minutes. That makes perfect rice every single time. If you are not using a rice cooker and you are cooking on the stove, practice, because there is a definite feel to making rice.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eWhat is the ratio of water to rice for perfect rice?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAgain, it\u0026rsquo;s the finger method. I don\u0026rsquo;t understand how it works scientifically because it doesn\u0026rsquo;t matter how much rice you have; the finger method works every single time.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv id=\"attachment_140131\" style=\"width: 1034px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-140131\" class=\"wp-image-140131 size-large\" src=\"https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/tuna-onigiri-feat.jpg?w=1024\" alt=\"Tuna onigiri on a plate\" width=\"1024\" height=\"682\" srcset=\"https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/tuna-onigiri-feat.jpg 1280w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/tuna-onigiri-feat.jpg?resize=300,200 300w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/tuna-onigiri-feat.jpg?resize=768,512 768w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/tuna-onigiri-feat.jpg?resize=1024,682 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\"\u003e\u003cp id=\"caption-attachment-140131\" class=\"wp-caption-text\"\u003eGet the recipe: \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/recipe/easy-tuna-onigiri/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003eTuna Onigiri\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eDoes all rice need to be soaked before cooking?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIdeally, it should be, but it depends on what you are doing with the rice. For the most part, if you are steaming your rice, you want to rinse it\u0026nbsp;a few times\u0026nbsp;to\u0026nbsp;clean it\u0026nbsp;and\u0026nbsp;allow it to slightly rehydrate. Parboiled rice, like boxed rice that can cook in minutes, does not need to be rinsed.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eWhat are your favourite ways to season rice?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI usually like to add star anise, a half stick of cinnamon and a little pinch of salt.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eDo you recommend seasoning rice before or after cooking?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI actually like seasoning my water just before cooking so I\u0026rsquo;ll add a pinch of salt.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv id=\"attachment_135187\" style=\"width: 1034px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-135187\" class=\"wp-image-135187 size-large\" src=\"https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/vegetable-pulao-feat.jpg?w=1024\" alt=\"Vegetable pulao, ready to serve\" width=\"1024\" height=\"682\" srcset=\"https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/vegetable-pulao-feat.jpg 1280w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/vegetable-pulao-feat.jpg?resize=300,200 300w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/vegetable-pulao-feat.jpg?resize=768,512 768w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/vegetable-pulao-feat.jpg?resize=1024,682 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\"\u003e\u003cp id=\"caption-attachment-135187\" class=\"wp-caption-text\"\u003eGet the recipe: \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/recipe/spiced-vegetable-pulao/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003eSpiced Vegetable Pulao\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eWhat less common rice varieties should our readers be trying?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSome of the other less common varieties to try are Riceberry Rice and Thai sticky rice which is also called glutinous or sweet rice. Riceberry rice is a long-grain rice, well-known for its deep purple hue, getting its distinctive colour from naturally occurring flavonoid pigments known to have antioxidant properties.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eDo you recommend cooking rice in a rice cooker or on the stovetop?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI always cook rice on a stovetop, but if you do have a very good rice cooker, it can be quite amazing. Kate [my wife] definitely swears by the Tiger Rice Cooker, but when I make rice and want it to come out absolutely perfect every single time, I do it on top of the stove using the finger method.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRead more: \u003ca href=\"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/article/leftover-rice-recipes/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003eLeftover Rice Recipes That Make Meal Prep So Much Easier\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\n","modified":"2023-05-18T09:44:36","date":"2023-06-08T09:00:39","uri":"https://www.foodnetwork.ca/article/how-to-make-the-best-rice-ever","slug":"how-to-make-the-best-rice-ever","featuredImage":{"__typename":"NodeWithFeaturedImageToMediaItemConnectionEdge","node":{"__typename":"MediaItem","title":"rice-closeup","altText":"Closeup on white rice","mediaItemUrl":"https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/rice-closeup.jpg","srcSet":"https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/rice-closeup.jpg 1280w, https://api.vip.foodnetwork.ca/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/rice-closeup.jp